<h2>
	Send a Webpage Best Practices:
</h2> 

<ul>

<li>
<p>Only send a webpage that has been formatted simply: use <strong>HTML tables</strong> for layout, 
	and <strong>inline css styles</strong> for text formatting. Javascript/Flash will not work in HTML email messages. 
	Layout using fancy css styles will not look good in every mail reader. 
</p>
</li>

<li>
	<p>Instead of setting a URL to grab a webpage, you may create an HTML message. Make sure all images and other resources
	use a fully quantified URL (starts with: <strong>http://</strong>) or images, links, etc may break. </p>
</li> 
<li>
	<p><strong>Always</strong> send a test message, to make sure layout and formatting look good! </p>
</li>
	
<li>Advanced Options allow you to embed images into the email message itself. Remember that this can 
	make your email message much larger in size!
</li> 

<li>
	<p>
	You only need to create an HTML version of your message
</p>
</li>

<li><p>
	You <strong>may</strong> create two versions of your message. 
	Both copies will be embedded in the same email you send. 
	Your PlainText version will be shown to users whose mail reader cannot view your HTML version. 
</p>
</li>


</ul>

